      "title": "Natural and Forced Convection",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Natural and Forced Convection</h3><p><strong>(a) Natural Convections</strong></p><p>In convections, heat transfers takes place due to motion of heated material and in natural convection this transfer is due to difference in density.</p><p><strong>(b) Forced Convection</strong></p><p>If the heated material is forced to move by any external source such as pump, fan etc., then such a convection is called forced convection.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:225/157;\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"225\" height=\"157\"></figure><p>Heat transfer through convection per unit time $\\left( \\frac{\\text{dQ}}{\\text{dt}} \\right)=\\text{hA}\\left( \\text{T}-{{\\text{T}}_{0}} \\right)$</p><p>Where,</p><p>$A\\equiv $ surface area of the body is contact with the fluids.</p><p>$\\text{h}\\equiv $ convection co-efficient which depend on the nature of the fluids in contact with the surface.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dbc6c03b9dcaf1afe35b"
    }
